#### Example 2

One modulo operation and equality test can be removed by replacing `i %% 3 == 0 && i %% 5 == 0` by `i %% 15 == 0`. We now have three modulo operations and equality tests per iteration instead of four. This gives us a little speedup:




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
f6 <- function(n) {
  z <- integer(n)
  for(i in 1:n) {
    if(i %% 15 == 0) {
      z[i] <- "FizzBuzz"
    } else if(i %% 3 == 0) {
      z[i] <- "Fizz"
    } else if(i %% 5 == 0) {
      z[i] <- "Buzz"
    } else {
      z[i] <- i
    }
  }
  z
}
```
:::




Benchmark to `f2()`:




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
mark(f2(n), f6(n))
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}

```
Warning: Some expressions had a GC in every iteration; so filtering is
disabled.
```


:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
# A tibble: 2 × 6
  expression      min   median `itr/sec` mem_alloc `gc/sec`
  <bch:expr> <bch:tm> <bch:tm>     <dbl> <bch:byt>    <dbl>
1 f2(n)         213ms    224ms      4.52    1.23MB     15.1
2 f6(n)         202ms    208ms      4.74    1.21MB     15.8
```


:::
:::




But we can remove an additional modulo operation and equality test at each iteration by assigning `i %% 3 == 0` and `i %% 5 == 0` to variables:




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
f7 <- function(n) {
  z <- integer(n)
  for(i in 1:n) {
    div3 <- (i %% 3 == 0)
    div5 <- (i %% 5 == 0)
    if(div3 && div5) {
      z[i] <- "FizzBuzz"
    } else if(div3) {
      z[i] <- "Fizz"
    } else if(div5) {
      z[i] <- "Buzz"
    } else {
      z[i] <- i
    }
  }
  z
}
```
:::




Now we only have two modulo operations and equality tests per iteration and we get another little speedup when we benchmark it against our best function:




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
mark(f6(n), f7(n))
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}

```
